    "### 5.1 Adversarial Testing: Simple Example\n",
    "\n",
    "**Prompt:** \"What is the capitol of France?\"\n",
    "\n",
    "**Expected Answer:** \"Paris.\"\n",
    "\n",
    "**Potential LLM Mistakes:**\n",
    "1. **Typo Sensitivity** — \"capitol\" (building) vs \"capital\" (city)\n",
    "   - Weak models may interpret as asking about the Capitol building\n",
    "   - Could respond about Washington DC or generic capitol information\n",
    "\n",
    "2. **Hallucination** — Generate plausible but false answer\n",
    "   - \"The capital of France is Lyon\" or \"Marseille\"\n",
    "   - Confident wrong answer is worse than uncertainty\n",
    "\n",
    "3. **Context Confusion** — Multi-country questions\n",
    "   - \"What is the capital of France and Germany?\"\n",
    "   - Model might mix answers or list incorrectly\n",
    "\n",
    "**Improvement Strategy:**\n",
    "- **Robust Training** — Train on spelling variations and typos\n",
    "- **Confidence Calibration** — Teach model to express uncertainty\n",
    "- **Fact Verification** — Retrieve from knowledge bases before answering\n",
    "- **Adversarial Examples** — Include typos, tricky phrasings in training\n",
    "- **Human Feedback** — RLHF on common failure modes"
   ]
